18:10.380 --> 18:16.120
Those who are at all familiar with Bryant's work have certainly come across his apparent fascination with sharks.

18:16.460 --> 18:22.600
Here he explains how this attraction was spawned, then how it led to the famous short story titled simply Shark.

18:23.620 --> 18:24.660
Why sharks?

18:26.540 --> 18:37.420
You know, when people visit my apartment, they see all sorts of shark paraphernalia, you know, jaws mounted on backboards and shark mobiles, shark paintings and so forth and so on.

18:38.360 --> 18:53.580
The reason for the shark motif and the reason that I suppose I've adopted the shark as a sort of totem is because in the early 70s, one of my closest friends had dreamed the night before.

18:53.800 --> 18:58.340
She told me about this at breakfast, that she had been in the body of a shark.

18:58.660 --> 19:02.960
She had seen the world through shark colored lenses.

19:05.160 --> 19:10.540
And we talked about this for a while, you know, got past the obvious Freudian symbolism of it all.

19:11.620 --> 19:13.600
And I was fascinated by the dream.

19:14.960 --> 19:21.240
Then she catalyzed action by saying, listen, why don't you write a story about sharks?

19:21.520 --> 19:23.180
Now, I didn't know anything about sharks.

19:23.180 --> 19:26.320
I was just an inland boy who'd grown up far from the sea.

19:26.320 --> 19:29.980
And although the ocean has always fascinated me, I didn't know about sharks.

19:30.160 --> 19:33.320
But I did my research, just as with, say, particle theory.

19:33.480 --> 19:34.980
I found out about sharks.

19:34.980 --> 19:42.280
I became intrigued by their position in the evolutionary scheme of things, how incredibly well developed they are.

19:42.280 --> 19:57.400
And I was also struck by such images as the fact that the shark is the major species of creature which is hostile to human beings, which is in no danger of extinction, at least at this point.

19:58.140 --> 20:08.060
So I took my friend's original dream and I said, okay, I've got a character who wants to be a shark.

20:08.340 --> 20:10.380
Why does she want to be a shark?

20:10.580 --> 20:14.660
How does she become a shark, both metaphorically and literally?

20:14.980 --> 20:18.360
And that's how the original shark story generated.

20:19.540 --> 20:30.820
I realized after finishing the story that there were other things that involved sharks that I had not dealt with in the story that I would treat in various other pieces.

20:38.700 --> 20:44.120
When Bryant's friends got wind of his newfound fascination, he began to be bombarded with shark mementos.

20:44.820 --> 20:51.620
What happened then, of course, was the older you get, I think the harder you are to shop for your friends and relatives.

20:51.940 --> 20:53.140
They don't know what to get you.

20:53.360 --> 20:54.720
They don't know what your tastes are.

20:54.820 --> 20:57.780
They don't know what books you've read or what albums you don't have.

20:59.880 --> 21:05.860
So somehow the shark story caught the fancy of the people around me and I started giving me shark paraphernalia.

21:05.960 --> 21:08.980
Before I knew it, I had more sharks than I knew what to do with.

21:09.620 --> 21:18.100
I'm glad it was sharks because, jaws notwithstanding, there never has been that much in the way of shark artifacts for sale.

21:18.300 --> 21:26.100
If it had been unicorns or dragons, say, I would have been swamped completely and utterly and I could have knick-knack and gee-gaw garage sales.

21:26.560 --> 21:29.620
But instead, I've got some pretty neat shark stuff.

21:29.980 --> 21:32.020
