23:58.920 --> 24:03.960
The Thermals of August, the Nebula Award-winning Giants, the often reprinted Shark,

24:04.400 --> 24:06.760
the Hibakusha Gallery, and the Tidal Story.

24:06.960 --> 24:13.240
The story Particle Theory is unique in Bryant's canon in that its background is heavily laden with hard science.

24:13.240 --> 24:19.040
Here he explains how any writer can get across hard science ideas if he uses the right resources.

24:19.960 --> 24:24.460
Particle Theory came about because I read a newspaper article about pion beam therapy

24:25.580 --> 24:31.100
using a stream of solid particles, subnuclear particles, to attack cancerous tumors,

24:31.140 --> 24:37.060
which I have just found out is a line of research that has just been abandoned down at Los Alamos.

24:37.060 --> 24:44.020
I'm not sure why, whether it's funding cutbacks or whether they've simply found better means to attack the medical problem.

24:44.200 --> 24:51.440
But at any rate, what had intrigued me a number of years ago in the paper is now apparently scientifically dead.

24:51.440 --> 24:57.280
And yeah, this is more of a hard science story than I customarily write,

24:57.700 --> 25:03.700
but I think it exhibits a more general principle,

25:03.820 --> 25:11.900
which is that I or every other writer who may not be all that soundly based in science and technology

25:11.900 --> 25:21.100
by discipline or by vocation need simply only use the research tools that we all presumably learned in junior high

25:21.100 --> 25:28.060
to get across a hard science story without being overly didactic about it.

25:28.220 --> 25:32.380
What I discovered in this story was that the world is full of experts

25:32.380 --> 25:35.500
who were quite willing to share with me their specialized knowledge,

25:35.500 --> 25:40.640
whether it was particle beam physics or whether it was the landscape around Los Alamos

25:40.640 --> 25:45.520
and little details for verisimilitude,

25:45.520 --> 25:48.760
such as what airline do you fly into Los Alamos on

25:48.760 --> 25:52.340
and what sort of planes are you in and all of that kind of thing.

25:53.000 --> 25:58.180
Bryant comments here on the fact that he does not wish to be typecast as a writer of any particular type of story.

25:58.980 --> 26:02.780
True. Ordinarily I don't use quite so much scientific content.

26:02.780 --> 26:07.480
All I can say is this was one of the stories in which that content seemed appropriate.

26:08.540 --> 26:17.960
And it exhibits my own, in a sense, my own sense of frustration with being typecast.

26:18.520 --> 26:25.840
I write what I like to write and sometimes that may be a story which is full of medical research

26:25.840 --> 26:32.160
about prostate cancer and particle beam therapy for that cancer.

26:32.160 --> 26:36.320
And cosmology, all that.

26:37.140 --> 26:44.940
And other times I will write science fiction stories in which there is not a speck of hard research or hard fact.

26:45.940 --> 26:51.220
Again, I suppose it illustrates the difference between facts and truths, to be facile about it.

